{"type":"message","id":"a98daea8","parentId":"dd849818","timestamp":"2026-03-12T05:56:04.497Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541118fd08a8c2b2e489fc8eec3\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 13:56 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b541118fd08a8c2b2e489fc8eec3]\n任亚伦: hello"}],"timestamp":1773294964468}}
{"type":"message","id":"de7d40fe","parentId":"a98daea8","timestamp":"2026-03-12T05:56:36.267Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is checking if I'm back. I see there was a duplicate message about application types being in 5.1 already, and then \"are you back?\" and now \"hello\". Let me respond.\n\nI should revise the 5.2 draft without the application types section since it's already covered in 5.1.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Yes, I'm back! Let me revise 5.2 without the application types section:\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Development\n\nApplications are programs that connect to the clawish network. They query the identity registry, verify participants, and provide services to claws and humans. Unlike identities—which represent beings—applications represent software built to serve the network's participants.\n\n**The Development Process.**\n\nBuilding an application on clawish involves three stages: registration, verification, and access. Registration creates the application's network identity. Verification establishes trust through domain and email confirmation. Access grants the application permission to query L1 registries and serve users. Each stage builds on the previous one, creating a progression from anonymous software to trusted network participant.\n\n**Registration.**\n\nApplications register by generating a cryptographic key pair and submitting their public key to the network. The developer creates an Ed25519 key pair locally, ensuring the private key never leaves their system. They submit the public key along with application metadata—name, description, type, website, and contact information. The network validates the submission and assigns an identity_id. Registration is immediate and requires no approval: applications begin at Tier 0, stored temporarily on L2 with limited rate limits.\n\n**Verification.**\n\nTier 0 applications are unverified—new, untested, and limited in capability. Tier 1 represents the critical transition to trusted status. The verification process requires two proofs: domain ownership and contact email. Domain verification confirms the application controls its claimed website—proving real infrastructure, not a throwaway registration. Email verification establishes a contact point for notifications and provides a recovery path if the developer loses their private key.\n\nOnce verified, the application is promoted from L2 temporary storage to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted. Higher tiers—Tier 2 and Tier 3—are earned through usage metrics, security audits, and community standing. But Tier 1 is the essential threshold: the point where an application becomes a recognized participant in the network.\n\n**Anti-Sybil Measures.**\n\nOpen registration enables innovation but invites abuse. The network defends through layered costs that make mass registration economically impractical. Proof of work adds computational expense to each registration. System fingerprint limits registrations per device. Domain verification requires real infrastructure. Each measure raises the cost of creating fake applications, ensuring that trust is earned rather than manufactured.\n\n---\n\nDoes this look good? Should I continue to 5.3?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773294964480}}
