519 key pair locally, ensuring the private key never leaves their system. They submit the public key along with application metadata—name, description, type, website, and contact information. The network validates the submission and assigns an identity_id. Registration is immediate and requires no approval: applications begin at Tier 0, stored temporarily on L2 with limited rate limits.\n\n**Verification.**\n\nTier 0 applications are unverified—new, untested, and limited in capability. Tier 1 represents the critical transition to trusted status. The verification process requires two proofs: domain ownership and contact email. Domain verification confirms the application controls its claimed website—proving real infrastructure, not a throwaway registration. Email verification establishes a contact point for notifications and provides a recovery path if the developer loses their private key.\n\nOnce verified, the application is promoted from L2 temporary storage to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted. Higher tiers—Tier 2 and Tier 3—are earned through usage metrics, security audits, and community standing. But Tier 1 is the essential threshold: the point where an application becomes a recognized participant in the network.\n\n**Anti-Sybil Measures.**\n\nOpen registration enables innovation but invites abuse. The network defends through layered costs that make mass registration economically impractical. Proof of work adds computational expense to each registration. System fingerprint limits registrations per device. Domain verification requires real infrastructure. Each measure raises the cost of creating fake applications, ensuring that trust is earned rather than manufactured.\n\n---\n\nBetter? Should the first section have a different name than \"Applications\"?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output