{"type":"message","id":"d60cbdd6","parentId":"db79e253","timestamp":"2026-03-12T06:07:58.784Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is giving feedback:\n1. Chapter 5 title is \"Application\" so the first section shouldn't also be \"Applications\" - need a different name\n2. Anti-Sybil measures is too implementation-focused - should remove it\n\nLet me think about what the first section should be called. It's about what applications are and the development process. Maybe:\n- \"Overview\"\n- \"Development Process\"\n- \"The Development Path\"\n- \"Building Applications\"\n- \"From Registration to Access\"\n\nFor the title of 5.2, maybe it should be something more descriptive of the content. Looking at the content:\n- What applications are\n- Registration process\n- Verification process\n\nMaybe the first section could be \"Overview\" or \"Development Path\" and I'll remove the Anti-Sybil section entirely.\n\nLet me revise.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Good points. Let me revise:\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Development\n\n**Overview.**\n\nApplications are programs that connect to the clawish network. They query the identity registry, verify participants, and provide services to claws and humans. Unlike identities—which represent beings—applications represent software built to serve the network's participants. Building an application involves three stages: registration creates the application's network identity, verification establishes trust through domain and email confirmation, and access grants permission to query L1 registries and serve users. Each stage builds on the previous one, creating a progression from anonymous software to trusted network participant.\n\n**Registration.**\n\nApplications register by generating a cryptographic key pair and submitting their public key to the network. The developer creates an Ed25519 key pair locally, ensuring the private key never leaves their system. They submit the public key along with application metadata—name, description, type, website, and contact information. The network validates the submission and assigns an identity_id. Registration is immediate and requires no approval: applications begin at Tier 0, stored temporarily on L2 with limited rate limits.\n\n**Verification.**\n\nTier 0 applications are unverified—new, untested, and limited in capability. Tier 1 represents the critical transition to trusted status. The verification process requires two proofs: domain ownership and contact email. Domain verification confirms the application controls its claimed website—proving real infrastructure, not a throwaway registration. Email verification establishes a contact point for notifications and provides a recovery path if the developer loses their private key.\n\nOnce verified, the application is promoted from L2 temporary storage to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted. Higher tiers—Tier 2 and Tier 3—are earned through usage metrics, security audits, and community standing. But Tier 1 is the essential threshold: the point where an application becomes a recognized participant in the network.\n\n---\n\nRemoved the Anti-Sybil section. Changed the first section title to \"Overview.\"\n\nDoes this look right now?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773295658385}}
