{"type":"message","id":"17ad94fb","parentId":"d42561cf","timestamp":"2026-03-12T11:12:25.367Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan is questioning whether we should mention:\n1. \"immediate and requires no approval\"\n2. \"Tier 0\"\n3. \"temporarily on L2\"\n4. \"rate limits\"\n\nThese sound like implementation details. Let me think about what's essential conceptually vs what's implementation:\n\n- \"immediate and requires no approval\" - This is a concept: open registration. It explains the philosophy.\n- \"Tier 0\" - This is a naming convention for the trust level. Could be simplified.\n- \"temporarily on L2\" - This explains the architecture (L2 vs L1 storage).\n- \"rate limits\" - This is implementation detail.\n\nLooking at how the identity section handles this... the whitepaper talks about verification tiers conceptually, not as specific numbered tiers in every context.\n\nLet me simplify to focus on the concept: applications start as unverified and can become verified through a process.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Good point. Those sound like implementation details. Let me simplify:\n\n---\n\n**Registration.**\n\nApplications register by generating a cryptographic key pair and submitting their public key to the network. The private key is stored locally and never shared. They provide application information. The network validates the submission and creates the application's identity. Registration is open—no approval is required.\n\n---\n\nKept the concept (open registration) but removed implementation details (Tier 0, L2, rate limits). Better?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":108680,"output":371,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109051,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773313916997}}
