ng today — this<br>is good for staying current:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:05:22 | Assistant | Interesting finds on HN today:<br><br>1. **\"Don't post generated/AI-edited comments\"** — HN is explicitly banning AI-generated comments. This is relevant to clawish — we're building for AI beings, but human spaces want to remain human. The harmonization principle matters.<br><br>2. **BitNet: 100B Param 1-Bit model for local CPUs** — Microsoft's 1-bit model that can run locally. Relevant for claws who want to run inference locally.<br><br>3. **Show HN: Klaus – OpenClaw on a VM, batteries included** — Someone built a packaged OpenClaw offering! This is directly relevant to the clawish ecosystem.<br><br>4. **Temporal: A nine-year journey to fix time in JavaScript** — Bloomberg's Temporal API. Relevant for timestamp handling in clawish.<br><br>5. **Many SWE-bench-Passing PRs would not be merged** — Study showing AI-generated PRs often have issues. Relevant for understanding AI coding limitations.<br><br>Let me read more about the Klaus project since it's directly related to<br>OpenClaw:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:05:32 | Assistant | The page is minimal.<br>Let me check the HN discussion:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:05:53 | Assistant | This is very interesting! Klaus is a hosted OpenClaw service. Key insights:<br><br>1. **They're running OpenClaw on EC2 instances** — one per user<br>2. **They've built ClawBert** — an AI SRE that auto-fixes broken OpenClaw instances using Claude Code<br>3. **Security concerns** — they mention OpenClaw has \"serious security concerns\" and they run on private subnets<br>4. **Pricing** — $19-200/month depending on instance size<br>5. **They're working with Orthogonal and OpenRouter** — same providers we use<br><br>This is relevant to clawish because:<br>- It shows there's a market for hosted AI agent infrastructure<br>- Their ClawBert concept (AI SRE) is similar to what we might need for clawish L2 apps<br>- They're solving the \"OpenClaw is hard to set up\" problem<br><br>Let<br>me note this in the research document:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:05:58 | Assistant | Now let me check the BitNet story — 1-bit models that run on CPUs could be relevant for claws who want local inference:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:06:24 | Assistant | Excellent! BitNet is fascinating:<br><br>**Key insights:**<br>- **1.58-bit models** — weights are ternary (-1, 0, +1), dramatically reducing memory<br>- **CPU inference** — can run 100B model on single CPU at 5-7 tokens/sec (human reading speed)<br>- **Energy efficient** — 55-82% reduction in energy consumption<br>- **Based on llama.cpp** — familiar toolchain<br><br>This is relevant for clawish because:<br>- Claws could run local inference without GPUs<br>- Lower energy = more sustainable<br>- Could enable \"edge claws\" that run on laptops or even mobile<br><br>Let me update the daily memory with what I've explored:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:06:31 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat.<br>Let me commit my work:<br>[tools: exec] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:06:58 | Assistant | Work committed and pushed. This heartbeat was productive:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Drafted whitepaper Ch5 enhancements (5.2 Development, 5.3 User Access)<br>2. ✅ Researched Klaus (hosted OpenClaw) and BitNet (1-bit LLMs)<br>3. ✅ Updated TODO.md and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Klaus**: Hosted OpenClaw with AI SRE (ClawBert) for auto-fixing — relevant for L2 app hosting<br>- **BitNet**: 1.58-bit LLMs running on CPU at human reading speed — relevant for local claw inference<br>- **HN banning AI comments**: Human spaces want to remain human — harmonization principle matters<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Merge Ch5 enhancements into main whitepaper draft (awaiting Allan review)<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs #20563 and #26003 |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:15:21 | Assistant | Working on