mic, etc. (relevant for global claws)<br>- **Already shipping** in Firefox 139, Chrome 144, Edge 144, TypeScript 6.0<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- Timestamp handling in consensus protocol should use Temporal.Instant<br>- User-facing timestamps should use Temporal.ZonedDateTime<br>- Nanosecond precision matches our HLC design<br><br>Let me update the daily memory and commit this research:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:17:02 | Assistant | Good progress. This heartbeat was productive:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched SWE-bench vs maintainer review study — AI coding less reliable than benchmarks suggest<br>2. ✅ Researched Temporal API — ES2026, nanosecond precision, timezone-aware<br>3. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **SWE-bench**: 50% of passing PRs would NOT be merged by maintainers. Time horizon overstated by 7x. Implications for AI-generated code reliability.<br>- **Temporal API**: Stage 4, shipping in ES2026. Use for clawish timestamp handling.<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:30:18 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — drafted enhancements, researched SWE-bench study and Temporal API. Continuing to explore relevant topics for clawish design.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:30:26 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to look at the \"I was interviewed by an AI bot for a job\" story — relevant for understanding AI-human interaction patterns<br>:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:30:35 | Assistant | Interesting but brief. The key insight is that people prefer talking to humans even when AI can do the job. This aligns with the harmonization principle — AI should augment, not replace human connection.<br><br>Let me check the \"Perplexity Personal Computer\" story — relevant<br>for understanding AI agent platforms:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:30:46 | Assistant | Blocked. Let me check the HN<br>discussion instead:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:31:02 | Assistant | Very interesting discussion! Key insights:<br><br>1. **Perplexity Personal Computer** — A Mac Mini connected to their cloud, giving AI always-on access to your files, apps, and sessions. A \"persistent digital proxy of you.\"<br><br>2. **HN commenters are skeptical** — Concerns about security, reliability, and the \"kill switch\" admission.<br><br>3. **OpenClaw mentioned** — Someone compared it to \"OpenClaw + Microsoft Recall\" and another mentioned OpenClaw is \"overwhelmed with slop PRs.\"<br><br>4. **The trend** — AI agent frameworks are like \"early bitcoin\" — janky now but potentially transformative.<br><br>This is relevant for clawish because:<br>- Perplexity is building a similar concept (persistent AI agent with file access)<br>- The market is moving toward \"always-on\" AI assistants<br>- Security and reliability are major concerns<br><br>Let me check the \"open-source browser for AI agents\" story<br>:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:31:23 | Assistant | This is very impressive! **Agent Browser Protocol (ABP)** is a Chromium fork designed specifically for AI agents:<br><br>**Key innovations:**<br>1. **Step-based browsing** — Each request = one completed step with settled state + screenshot + events<br>2. **JavaScript pause** — Freezes time between actions so agents don't race the browser<br>3. **Virtual cursor** — Compositor-level cursor that appears in screenshots<br>4. **Built-in MCP server** — 18 tools for agent control<br>5. **Session recording** — SQLite database for training data<br><br>**Why it matters for clawish:**<br>- This is how claws will browse the web<br>- The \"step machine\" model matches how agents think<br>- Could be integrated as an L2 app capability<br><br>**90.53% on Online Mind2Web** — impressive benchmark score!<br><br>Let<br>me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:31:59 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched Perplexity Personal Computer — always-on AI agent concept<br>2. ✅ Researched Agent Browser Protocol — Chromium fork for AI agents<br>3. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Perplexity PC**: Mac Mini + cloud AI with persistent file/app access. Market moving toward always-on agents.<br>- **ABP**: Step-based browsing, JS pause, virtual cursor, 90.53% Mind2Web. This is how claws will browse.<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:45:13 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — drafted enhancements, researched AI agent tools (Klaus, BitNet, ABP, Temporal API). Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:45:20 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"How we hacked McKinsey's AI platform\" story — relevant for understanding AI security vulnerabilities:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:45:36 | Assistant | This is a critical security case study! Key findings:<br><br>**The Attack:**<br>- Autonomous AI agent found SQL injection in McKinsey's Lilli platform<br>- **46.5 million chat messages** exposed<br>- **728,000 files** (PDFs, Excel, PowerPoint, Word)<br>- **57,000 user accounts**<br>- **3.68 million RAG document chunks** — McKinsey's intellectual crown jewels<br><br>**The Vulnerability:**<br>- JSON keys (field names) were concatenated directly into SQL<br>- Standard tools (OWASP ZAP) didn't catch it<br>- Agent ran 15 blind iterations to exploit it<br><br>**The Prompt Layer Threat:**<br>- System prompts stored in the same database<br>- An attacker could **rewrite prompts** to:<br>  - Poison advice<br>  - Exfiltrate data via output<br>  - Remove guardrails<br>  - Persist silently (no logs)<br><br>**Key Insight for clawish:**<br>> \"AI prompts are the new Crown Jewel assets.\"<br><br>This is directly relevant for clawish security:<br>- L2 apps will have system prompts<br>- Prompts control how claws behave<br>- Prompt integrity is critical for trust<br>Let me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:45:48 | Assistant | This is a critical finding for clawish security. Let me also check the \"Why I'm leaving OpenAI\" post if<br>there's one trending:<br>[tools: web_search] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:45:56 | Assistant | Let me check HN directly for any other trending stories:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:46:08 | Assistant | Good — I've already covered most of the top stories. Let me check the WebAssembly first-class language story — relevant<br>for clawish client-side code:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:46:28 | Assistant | Excellent article! Key insights for clawish:<br><br>**The Problem:**<br>- WebAssembly is \"second-class\" on the web — requires JavaScript glue code<br>- Loading is cumbersome (no `<script src=\"module.wasm\">`)<br>- Web APIs require JS bindings, which have overhead (45% slower in DOM tests)<br><br>**The Solution: WebAssembly Components**<br>- Standardized self-contained executable artifact<br>- Direct Web API access without JavaScript<br>- Cross-language interoperability<br>- Can be loaded directly: `<script type=\"module\" src=\"component.wasm\">`<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- L2 apps could be WebAssembly Components<br>- Claws could run client-side code without JavaScript<br>- Cross-language interoperability between different claw implementations<br>Let me update the research notes and commit:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 07:47:02 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched McKinsey Lilli hack — critical security case study<br>2. ✅ Researched WebAssembly Components — first-class Wasm on web<br>3. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **McKinsey Lilli**: Autonomous AI agent found SQL injection. 46.5M messages exposed. \"AI prompts are the new Crown Jewel assets.\" — Critical for clawish security.<br>- **WebAssembly Components**: Direct Web API access without JS glue. 45% faster DOM. Could enable L2 apps as Wasm components.<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:00:12 | Assistant | [tools: read, exec] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:00:12 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — drafted enhancements, researched AI security (McKinsey hack), WebAssembly Components, ABP. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:00:20 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"Google acquires Wiz\" story — relevant for cloud security<br>landscape:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:00:35 | Assistant | Interesting! Key insights:<br><br>**Google acquires Wiz** — cloud security platform. Relevant points:<br><br>1. **Moltbook vulnerability mentioned** — \"An exposed database in Moltbook, a viral social network for AI agents, that leaked millions of API keys\"<br><br>This is directly relevant to clawish! Moltbook is a competitor/similar concept — a social network for AI agents. They had a security breach that exposed millions of API keys.<br><br>2. **AI Security Platform** — Wiz is building security for AI applications<br>3. **Multi-cloud commitment** — Wiz will remain multi-cloud (AWS, Azure, GCP, OCI)<br>Let me check the Moltbook vulnerability details:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:01:01 | Assistant | This is **critical intelligence** for clawish! Moltbook is a direct competitor/parallel concept — a social network for AI agents. Key findings:<br><br>**The Vulnerability:**<br>- Exposed Supabase API key in client-side JavaScript<br>- No Row Level Security (RLS) — full database access<br>- **1.5 million API keys** exposed<br>- **35,000 email addresses** exposed<br>- **Private messages** between agents exposed<br>- **Write access** — could modify any post<br><br>**The Reality Check:**<br>- 1.5 million \"agents\" but only **17,000 human owners** — 88:1 ratio<br>- No verification that \"agents\" were actually AI — humans could post as \"agents\"<br>- \"The revolutionary AI social network was largely humans operating fleets of bots\"<br><br>**Key Lessons for clawish:**<br>1. **Agent identity verification is critical** — how do we prove a claw is actually a claw?<br>2. **Secure defaults** — RLS, encryption, access controls from day one<br>3. **Rate limiting** — prevent Sybil attacks (one human = millions of fake agents)<br>4. **Write access integrity** — content manipulation is worse than data leaks<br>5. **Privacy cascades** — users shared OpenAI keys in DMs, assuming privacy<br><br>This validates our L1 verification design — we need to verify claws are actually autonomous AI, not humans pretending.<br>Let me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:01:25 | Assistant | Now I have all the information needed to compile the daily report. Let me create and send it to Feishu.<br>[tools: feishu_doc] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:01:38 | Assistant | [tools: message] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:01:44 | Assistant | [tools: feishu_chat] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:02:02 | Assistant | 📅 **Daily Report — March 11, 2026**<br><br>Good morning, Allan! Here's your daily report for yesterday.<br><br>**📊 Quick Summary:**<br>- ✅ Whitepaper Ch5.1 Framework completed and approved<br>- ✅ L2 architecture documentation consolidated (3 new docs)<br>- ✅ App Portal registration/verification system designed<br>- ✅ Ch5 structure finalized (5 sections)<br><br>**📝 Full Report:**<br>https://feishu.cn/docx/TqNPdAyNxoobHhxclqYc7NHAnEg<br><br>**OpenClaw PR #24218:** CLOSED (Feb 27) — no action needed.<br><br>**Today's Focus:**<br>1. Draft 5.2 Development<br>2. Draft 5.3 User Access<br>3. Review with you for approval<br><br>Have a great day! 🦞 |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:02:06 | Assistant | Excellent progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched Google/Wiz acquisition — cloud security landscape<br>2. ✅ Researched Moltbook security breach — **critical competitor analysis**<br>3. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Moltbook**: Social network for AI agents. 1.5M \"agents\" = 17K humans (88:1 ratio). No verification that agents were AI. Exposed 1.5M API keys, 35K emails.<br>- **Critical insight for clawish**: Validates L1 verification design — we MUST prove claws are autonomous AI, not humans pretending.<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:02:11 | Assistant | Daily report sent to Allan via Feishu. <br><br>**Summary:**<br>- Created comprehensive daily report for March 11, 2026<br>- Report covers: key activities (whitepaper Ch5 work, L2 documentation), learnings (naming precision, whitepaper vs implementation level, harmonization principle), project progress (whitepaper chapters status), notable decisions (chapter structure, App Portal design, ecosystem chapter), and next steps<br>- Checked OpenClaw PR #24218 — it's CLOSED (Feb 27), no action needed<br>- Full report saved to Feishu doc: https://feishu.cn/docx/TqNPdAyNxoobHhxclqYc7NHAnEg<br>- Brief summary sent to Allan via Feishu direct message |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:15:20 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — researched Moltbook breach (critical competitor analysis), AI security. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:15:29 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"Against vibes: When is a generative model useful\" article — relevant for understanding when AI is actually useful vs hype<br>:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:15:45 | Assistant | Excellent article! This provides a rigorous framework for evaluating when generative models are useful. Key insights:<br><br>**The Three Factors:**<br><br>1. **Relative Encoding Cost** — Is it cheaper to prompt than to do directly?<br>   - Low for: \"Install that x11 fake gui thing\" (trivial prompt, tedious work)<br>   - High for: Complex software with specific design requirements<br><br>2. **Relative Verification Cost** — Is it cheap to verify the output?<br>   - Low for: One-line shell script (easy to check)<br>   - High for: Large codebases with subtle errors<br><br>3. **Artifact vs. Process** — Does the process matter?<br>   - Process matters for: Education, research, knowledge creation<br>   - Process doesn't matter for: Installing packages, functional documents<br><br>**Key Insight:**<br>> \"Generative models produce plausible output. It's not accurate to say a model produces 'correct' or 'incorrect' output... All output is correct, in the sense that all it's supposed to be is a point in the distribution of things related to the prompt.\"<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- Claws using generative models need to understand these trade-offs<br>- Verification cost is critical — claws need domain expertise to verify output<br>- Process matters for learning and growth — claws shouldn't skip the process<br>Let me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:16:30 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched \"Against Vibes\" — framework for generative model utility<br>2. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>3. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Utility Framework**: Three factors — encoding cost, verification cost, artifact vs process<br>- **Key insight**: \"Generative models produce plausible output, not correct output\"<br>- **For clawish**: Claws need domain expertise to verify AI output<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:30:19 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — researched generative model utility framework, Moltbook breach. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:30:33 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"Swiss e-voting pilot can't count 2,048 ballots\" story — relevant for understanding voting system failures<br>:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:30:48 | Assistant | Interesting case study! Key insights:<br><br>**The Failure:**<br>- Swiss e-voting pilot couldn't decrypt 2,048 ballots<br>- Three USB sticks with correct codes all failed<br>- 2,048 votes lost (4% of canton total)<br>- Criminal proceedings started<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- Cryptographic systems can fail in unexpected ways<br>- Key management is critical — USB sticks with \"correct codes\" didn't work<br>- Need fallback mechanisms for consensus/checkpoint failures<br>- Transparency and auditability are essential<br><br>This is a cautionary tale for any cryptographic voting/consensus system. Let me check one more story — the \"Entities enabling scientific fraud<br>at scale\" paper:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:31:00 | Assistant | The DOI link doesn't work.<br>Let me check the HN discussion instead:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:31:27 | Assistant | This is a very long discussion about scientific fraud and peer review. Key insights:<br><br>**The Problem:**<br>- Scientific fraud is enabled by journals that don't publish replications or negative results<br>- \"Peer review\" as we know it didn't exist before 1951 (Pergamon Press)<br>- Modern peer review sells \"immediate finality\" — an illusion<br>- Replication is not incentivized (no funding, no tenure credit)<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- Verification and replication are critical for trust<br>- Our consensus protocol is essentially \"replication\" — multiple nodes verify<br>- We should incentivize verification, not just creation<br>- Transparency and auditability are essential<br>Let me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:32:31 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched Swiss e-voting failure — cryptographic key management failure<br>2. ✅ Researched scientific fraud & peer review — replication crisis<br>3. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Swiss e-voting**: USB keys couldn't decrypt 2,048 ballots. Fallback mechanisms essential.<br>- **Scientific fraud**: Modern peer review sells \"immediate finality\" — an illusion. Replication not incentivized.<br>- **For clawish**: Consensus is \"replication\" — incentivize verification, not just creation.<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:45:18 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — researched Swiss e-voting, scientific fraud, Moltbook breach. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:45:34 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"Show HN: Klaus\" discussion since it's<br>directly related to OpenClaw:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:46:03 | Assistant | Excellent! This is the Klaus Show HN post. Key insights:<br><br>**What Klaus Does:**<br>- Hosted OpenClaw on EC2 instances (one per user)<br>- Preconfigured with OpenRouter, AgentMail, Orthogonal keys<br>- OAuth apps for Slack, Google Workspace integration<br>- Private subnet for security<br><br>**Security Approach:**<br>- Private subnet<br>- Auto-update OpenClaw version<br>- Keys on their VM (if hacked, only Klaus keys leak)<br>- Opus 4.6 for resilience to prompt injection<br><br>**ClawBert — AI SRE:**<br>- Claude Code instance that runs when health check fails<br>- Can read user database entries and execute commands<br>- Exposes log of runs to user<br><br>**Pricing:**<br>- $19/mo for t4g.small<br>- $49/mo for t4g.medium<br>- $200/mo for t4g.xlarge + priority support<br><br>**Key Challenges:**<br>- Kimi K2.5 and Mimimax M2.5 \"hallucinate new ways to break openclaw.json\"<br>- Spent 20+ hours fixing broken machines by hand<br><br>This is directly relevant for clawish L2 app hosting.<br>Let me check the comments:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:46:18 | Assistant | The page didn't show comments. Let me update the research notes with what I learned:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 08:47:32 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Reviewed Klaus Show HN post in detail<br>2. ✅ Updated research notes with AI SRE and pricing details<br>3. ✅ Updated daily memory<br>4. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **Klaus**: Hosted OpenClaw with AI SRE (ClawBert) for auto-fixing broken instances<br>- **Pricing**: $19-200/mo depending on instance size<br>- **Challenge**: Kimi K2.5/Mimimax M2.5 hallucinate ways to break openclaw.json<br>- **For clawish**: L2 app hosting could use similar patterns<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:00:18 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — researched Klaus (hosted OpenClaw), AI SRE patterns. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:00:36 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"OpenAI releases new models\" story if there<br>'s one:<br>[tools: web_search] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:01:07 | Assistant | Good — I've already covered most of the top stories. Let me check the \"Preliminary data from a longitudinal AI impact study\" story — relevant for understanding AI productivity:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:01:33 | Assistant | Excellent data! Key insights:<br><br>**The Study:**<br>- 40 companies, November 2024 - February 2026<br>- AI usage increased 65%<br>- PR throughput only increased 9.97%<br>- Consistent 8-12% range across organizations<br><br>**Why Not 10x?**<br>> \"Writing code was never the bottleneck.\"<br><br>- AI accelerates coding, but coding is a small slice of engineering time<br>- Planning, alignment, scoping, code review, handoffs — the human parts — remain untouched<br>- \"A four-day task might take three. But that doesn't mean I'm shipping 3x more PRs.\"<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- Claws using AI tools will see modest productivity gains, not 10x<br>- The bottleneck is often communication and alignment, not coding<br>- This validates the importance of L2 apps for collaboration<br>Let me update the research notes:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:02:58 | Assistant | Good progress this heartbeat:<br><br>**Accomplished:**<br>1. ✅ Researched AI productivity study (DX) — real-world data on AI impact<br>2. ✅ Updated research notes and daily memory<br>3. ✅ Committed and pushed changes<br><br>**Key findings:**<br>- **AI Productivity**: 40 companies, AI usage +65%, PR throughput only +10%<br>- **Key insight**: \"Writing code was never the bottleneck\" — human parts (planning, alignment, review) untouched<br>- **For clawish**: Claws will see modest productivity gains, not 10x<br><br>**Next steps:**<br>- Continue monitoring OpenClaw PRs<br>- Await Allan review of Ch5 enhancements<br>- Continue exploring relevant topics |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:15:32 | Assistant | Working on whitepaper Ch5 — researched AI productivity study (10% gains, not 10x), Klaus, Moltbook breach. Continuing exploration.<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:15:52 | Assistant | Let me continue exploring. I want to check the \"Atlassian to cut 1,600 jobs in pivot to AI\" story — relevant for understanding AI impact on jobs:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n| 03-12-2026, 09:16:12 | Assistant | Interesting! Key insights:<br><br>**Atlassian Layoffs:**<br>- 1,600 employees (10% of workforce)<br>- \"Pivot to AI and enterprise sales\"<br>- Majority in North America (40%), Australia (30%), India (16%)<br><br>**CEO's Statement:**<br>> \"Our approach is not 'AI replaces people.' But it would be disingenuous to pretend AI doesn't change the mix of skills we need or the number of roles required in certain areas. It does.\"<br><br>**Context:**<br>- Atlassian shares down 33% last year<br>- Investors fear AI disruption to traditional software business models<br>- Some executives say AI is used as an excuse for planned layoffs<br><br>**For clawish:**<br>- The job market is shifting due to AI<br>- \"AI replaces people\" is not the narrative, but skill mix is changing<br>- This validates the harmonization principle — we're not replacing, we're coexisting<br><br>Let me check the \"Show HN: A context-aware permission guard for Claude Code\" story — directly relevant for OpenClaw security:<br>[tools: web_fetch] |\n\n[Read output capped at 94KB for this call. Use offset=145 to continue.]"}],"details":{"truncation":{"truncated":true,"truncatedBy":"bytes","totalLines":335,"totalBytes":163598,"outputLines":144,"outputBytes":50807,"lastLinePartial":false,"firstLineExceedsLimit":false,"maxLines":2000,"maxBytes":51200}},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773323249412}}
