ish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.<br><br>**Registration.**<br><br>Applications register by generating a cryptographic key pair and submitting their public key to the network. The developer creates an Ed25519 key pair locally, ensuring the private key never leaves their system. They submit the public key along with application metadata—name, description, type, website, and contact information. The network validates the submission and assigns an identity_id. Registration is immediate and requires no approval: applications begin at Tier 0, stored temporarily on L2 with limited rate limits.<br><br>**Verification.**<br><br>Tier 0 applications are unverified—new, untested, and limited in capability. Tier 1 represents the critical transition to trusted status. The verification process requires two proofs: domain ownership and contact email. Domain verification confirms the application controls its claimed website—proving real infrastructure, not a throwaway registration. Email verification establishes a contact point for notifications and provides a recovery path if the developer loses their private key.<br><br>Once verified, the application is promoted from L2 temporary storage to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted. Higher tiers—Tier 2 and Tier 3—are earned through usage metrics, security audits, and community standing. But Tier 1 is the essential threshold: the point where an application becomes a recognized participant in the network.<br><br>Ready to continue to 5.3 User Access? |\n| 03-12-2026, 17:41:08 | Assistant | Working with Allan on whitepaper Ch5 — 5.2 Development section complete, ready to continue to 5.3 User Access. |\n| 03-12-2026, 17:47:05 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541cf7b0f0b8c14d1298ea1d9bc\",<br>  \"sender_i