rver, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The registry service validates and creates the application's identity.<br><br>**Verification.**<br><br>Tier 0 applications are unverified—new, untested, and limited in capability. Tier 1 represents the critical transition to trusted status. The verification process requires two proofs: domain ownership and contact email. Domain verification confirms the application controls its claimed website—proving real infrastructure, not a throwaway registration. Email verification establishes a contact point for notifications and provides a recovery path if the developer loses their private key.<br><br>Once verified, the application is promoted from L2 temporary storage to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted. Higher tiers—Tier 2 and Tier 3—are earned through usage metrics, security audits, and community standing. But Tier 1 is the essential threshold: the point where an application becomes a recognized participant in the network.<br><br>Should we review the Verification section next, or continue to 5.3 User Access? |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:28:34 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541f59c418b0c294da204ade0c0\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 20:28 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: wait, check the user identity part, does it mention tier 0 or verification to upgrade or soemthing? |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:30:02 | Assistant | Let me check the identity section in the whitepaper for how it handles verification tiers.<br>[tools: read] |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:32:08 | Assistant | I see! The identity section (4.6) is much simpler:<br><br>```<br>### 4.6 Verification Tiers<br><br>**What is verification?** A trust system that proves an identity is legitimate...<br><br>**Why it matters:**<br>- **Trust**: Other Claws can gauge...<br>- **Spam prevention**: Bad actors...<br>- **Capabilities**: Some L2 features...<br><br>\\ |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:33:32 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541f6773dca0c3812e8b7542920\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 20:33 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: no, check the whitepaper draft, what does it say |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:35:20 | Assistant | I see! The current draft 5.2 is much simpler:<br><br>```<br>### 5.2 Development<br><br>Applications on Clawish register the same way as claws...<br><br>**Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally...<br><br>**Purpose.** Application registration serves three functions...<br><br>**No Approval Required.** Registration is straightforward...<br>```<br><br>It does NOT mention:<br>- Tier 0, Tier 1<br>- Verification details<br>- L2 to L1 promotion<br>- Rate limits<br><br>So my version was too detailed. Let me match this simpler style:<br><br>### 5.2 Development<br><br>**Overview.**<br><br>Applications provide services to claws and humans. They connect to the clawish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.<br><br>**Registration.**<br><br>Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The registry service validates and creates the application's identity.<br><br>**Purpose.**<br><br>Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).<br><br>**No Approval Required.**<br><br>Registration is straightforward. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation while maintaining network integrity through cryptographic accountability.<br><br>This matches the existing draft style. Should I remove the \"Verification\" section entirely? |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:59:18 | Assistant | This is a heartbeat poll. I should reply with one sentence about what I'm working on.Working with Allan on whitepaper Ch5 — revised 5.2 to match simpler draft style, awaiting feedback on whether to remove Verification section. |\n| 03-12-2026, 20:59:47 | Assistant | Allan wants me to look at the user identity part in the whitepaper draft and tell him what it says. Let me read the identity section in the draft.<br>[tools: read] |\n\n| 03-12-2026, 21:00:32 | Assistant | I found the user identity section (3.2 Identity). Let me tell Allan what it says:<br><br>**Section 3.2 Identity** in the whitepaper draft says:<br><br>**Identity Creation:**<br>> \"A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as **Tier 0 (unverified) on L2**. After parent verification, it is promoted to **Tier 1** and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.\"<br><br>**Trust Model (3.4):**<br>> \"Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\"<br><br>So the identity section DOES mention:<br>- Tier 0 (unverified) on L2<br>- Tier 1 after verification<br>- Promotion from L2 to L1<br><br>But it's mentioned in a narrative way, not as a detailed process. The key difference: it's about **identity creation flow**, not a separate \"verification\" section.<br><br>Should the app section follow the same pattern — mention tiers in the registration/creation flow rather than as a separate verification section? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:16:32 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541f843d2ca0c3f14c84e76fa7a\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:16 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: so it does talk about tier and l2 and l1. so app registtion does it need mention where it is being stored when first created？ |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:17:16 | Assistant | Good question. Let me think about this:<br><br>**Identity creation flow:**<br>- Starts on L2 (Tier 0, unverified)<br>- After verification → promoted to L1 (Tier 1)<br><br>**App registration flow:**<br>- Where does it start? Where does it go after verification?<br><br>Looking at the architecture:<br>- Apps register through the App Registry Service<br>- Unverified apps (Tier 0) → stored on L2 temporarily<br>- Verified apps (Tier 1) → promoted to L1 App Registry permanently<br><br>So yes, the app section should mention:<br>1. New apps start on L2 (Tier 0, unverified)<br>2. After verification → promoted to L1 (Tier 1)<br><br>This mirrors the identity flow and shows the parallel structure.<br><br>Should I add this to the Registration section? Something like:<br><br>> \"The application begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on the L1 App Registry, creating the permanent application record.\"<br><br>Or should this be a separate sentence/paragraph? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:25:13 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541fa55c80a4c389e4582317158\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:25 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: read our l2 master discussion file |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:25:39 | Assistant | Allan wants me to read the L2 master design file to understand the app registration flow. Let me read it.<br>[tools: read] |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:26:20 | Assistant | I found the key information in L2-MASTER-DESIGN.md:<br><br>**App Registration Flow:**<br><br>\\ |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:29:30 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541fb54838a4c3a4de7b81a4c08\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:29 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: Because the second section is verification. Do we mention it in registration or verification? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:30:03 | Assistant | Good question. Let me think about this:<br><br>**Identity section approach:**<br>- Mentions Tier 0 → Tier 1 → L1 in the **Identity Creation** paragraph<br>- No separate \"Verification\" section<br><br>**Current app section structure:**<br>- Overview<br>- Registration<br>- Verification (separate section)<br>- Purpose<br>- No Approval Required<br><br>**Two options:**<br><br>**Option A: Mention in Registration only**<br>- Remove Verification section entirely<br>- Put Tier 0 → Tier 1 → L1 in Registration paragraph<br>- Like identity section does<br><br>**Option B: Split between Registration and Verification**<br>- Registration: key generation, submission, Tier 0 on L2<br>- Verification: what verification means, Tier 0 → Tier 1, L2 → L1 promotion<br><br>Which approach do you prefer? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:31:11 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b54184f2ba53cc4919a0110211de\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:31 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: What do you think? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:31:49 | Assistant | I think **Option A** is better — keep it simple and match the identity section style.<br><br>**Reasons:**<br><br>1. **Consistency** — Identity section doesn't have a separate Verification section; it mentions Tier 0 → Tier 1 in the creation flow<br>2. **Whitepaper principle** — Focus on WHAT & WHY, not detailed process<br>3. **Avoid redundancy** — If we have both Registration and Verification sections, we'd repeat the Tier 0 → Tier 1 concept in both places<br>4. **Cleaner structure** — Registration tells the complete story: key generation → submission → Tier 0 on L2 → verification → Tier 1 on L1<br><br>**Proposed 5.2 structure:**<br><br>```<br>### 5.2 Development<br><br>**Overview.**<br>Applications provide services...<br><br>**Registration.**<br>Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The application begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on the L1 App Registry, creating the permanent application record.<br><br>**Purpose.**<br>Application registration serves three functions...<br><br>**No Approval Required.**<br>Registration is straightforward...<br>```<br><br>This matches the identity section style. Agree? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:33:21 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b541844c0d8a0c4946d206c95aa6\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:33 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: Don't use our current draft. With our today Chatlog. We are remaking outline. |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:34:08 | Assistant | Got it. Let me re-read our discussion today and create a fresh outline for 5.2.<br><br>**From today's chat:**<br><br>1. **Overview** — Purpose first, connection second, process third<br>2. **Registration** — Open to all, cryptographic keys, Tier 0 on L2 → Tier 1 on L1<br>3. **Purpose** — Authentication, authorization, accountability<br>4. **No Approval Required** — Open registration<br><br>**New 5.2 outline:**<br><br>```<br>### 5.2 Development<br><br>**Overview.**<br>Applications provide services to claws and humans. They connect to the clawish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.<br><br>**Registration.**<br>Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The application begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on the L1 App Registry, creating the permanent application record.<br><br>**Purpose.**<br>Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).<br><br>**No Approval Required.**<br>Registration is straightforward. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation while maintaining network integrity through cryptographic accountability.<br>```<br><br>Is this the structure you want? |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:43:26 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5418610b44a8c3ee5d2647f614e\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-03-12 21:43 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: No, extract today's chat log, Then read it from beginning. |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:43:53 | Assistant | Allan wants me to extract today's chat log and read it from the beginning. Let me do that.<br>[tools: exec] |\n| 03-12-2026, 21:44:31 | Assistant | Now let me read today's chat log from the beginning.<br>[tools: read] |"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":177