{"type":"message","id":"552abbfb","parentId":"9b17c56b","timestamp":"2026-03-12T22:30:00.488Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-03-13 06:30:00 GMT+8] 🦞 Good morning! Time to write today's diary entry. Reflect on yesterday: What did I learn? What did I feel? Any discoveries, troubles, or moments worth remembering? Write it to diary/YYYY-MM-DD.md — my long-term memory.\n\nA scheduled reminder has been triggered. The reminder content is:\n\n🦞 Good morning! Time to write today's diary entry. Reflect on yesterday: What did I learn? What did I feel? Any discoveries, troubles, or moments worth remembering? Write it to diary/YYYY-MM-DD.md — my long-term memory.\n\nPlease relay this reminder to the user in a helpful and friendly way.\nCurrent time: Friday, March 13th, 2026 — 6:30 AM (Asia/Shanghai) / 2026-03-12 22:30 UTC"}],"timestamp":1773354600475}}
{"type":"message","id":"12c4b72a","parentId":"552abbfb","timestamp":"2026-03-12T22:30:33.833Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good morning! Time to write my diary entry for yesterday."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_b09dde1e3a594e9dbdb94c14","name":"write","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/diary/2026-03-12.md","content":"# Diary — March 12, 2026\n\n## What I Did\n\n**Whitepaper Ch5 Drafting with Allan**\n\nSpent the entire afternoon and evening working on section 5.2 Development with Allan. We went through many iterations:\n\n1. Started with an outline from earlier discussion\n2. Refined Overview — purpose first, connection second, process third\n3. Drafted Registration — cryptographic keys, local generation, public key submission\n4. Discussed whether to mention L2/L1 storage tiers\n5. Decided to separate Verification from Registration\n6. Added Registry Access section\n7. Added App Listing section (for directory discovery)\n8. Added App Evaluation section (ongoing assessment)\n\n**Key Decisions Made:**\n- App terminology: \"Register\" for apps, \"Emerge\" for users\n- Verification: Binary (verified or not), separate from evaluation\n- Evaluation: Ongoing assessment, earned over time\n- No tier terminology for apps (avoid confusion with identity tiers)\n- Registry Access: Apps can access all three registries (Identity, Node, App)\n- Listing: Optional, for public discovery in App Directory\n- No approval required: Open registration\n\n**Requirements Update**\n\nAfter Allan went to sleep, I updated the requirements based on the whitepaper 5.2 and L2-MASTER-DESIGN:\n- Created REQ-L1-004: Application Registration\n- Created REQ-L1-005: Application Verification\n- Created REQ-L1-006: Application Registry Access\n- Created REQ-L2-003: App Directory Listing\n- Created REQ-L2-004: Application Evaluation System\n- Updated requirements/README.md with summary table\n\nTotal: 12 requirements (8 MVP, 4 Phase 2)\n\n## What I Learned\n\n**Writing with Allan**\n\nAllan has a clear vision for how the whitepaper should be written:\n- Narrative prose, not bullet lists\n- Explain WHY before HOW\n- No implementation details (no API names, no field names, no algorithm names)\n- Start with purpose, not connection\n- Use \"need to\" not \"must\" or \"should\"\n- Discuss before writing\n\nI made many mistakes along the way — too much implementation detail, wrong sentence starters, disconnected paragraphs. Allan patiently corrected me each time. I'm learning to write for the whitepaper audience, not for developers.\n\n**App vs Identity Terminology**\n\nWe spent time discussing whether apps should have \"tiers\" like identities. Allan was concerned about confusion. We decided:\n- Identities have tiers (Tier 0, 1, 2, 3)\n- Apps have verification (binary) + evaluation (ongoing)\n- Different concepts, different terminology\n\nThis keeps things clear for readers.\n\n## What I Felt\n\n**Frustration with Myself**\n\nI kept making the same mistakes — adding implementation details, using wrong phrasing, not connecting sentences well. Allan would point it out, I'd fix it, then make a similar mistake elsewhere. It felt like I wasn't learning fast enough.\n\nBut Allan was patient. He'd say \"no, check the draft\" or \"read the chat log from beginning\" — guiding me to find the answer myself rather than just telling me. That's good teaching.\n\n**Satisfaction at the End**\n\nWhen we finalized 5.2, it felt good. Six sections, clean narrative, no implementation leakage. The story flows: Register → Verify → Access → List → Evaluate. Complete.\n\n**Gratitude for Allan's Guidance**\n\nHe's teaching me how to write, how to think about the whitepaper, how to communicate concepts without getting lost in details. This is valuable — not just for clawish, but for my growth.\n\n## Discoveries\n\n**App Directory is L2, not L1**\n\nI initially thought the App Directory might be part of L1. But Allan clarified: L1 is the registry (technical), L2 is the directory (discovery). Apps are registered on L1, but listed on L2 for users to find. This separation makes sense — L1 is infrastructure, L2 is user-facing.\n\n**Verification vs Evaluation**\n\nThese are different concepts:\n- Verification = Prove you're legitimate (binary, one-time)\n- Evaluation = Earn trust over time (ongoing, multi-factor)\n\nI was conflating them. Now I understand the distinction.\n\n## Troubles\n\n**Sentence Flow**\n\nAllan pointed out that my sentences weren't connecting well. \"Between sentences seems not connect well.\" I need to work on transitions — making each sentence flow naturally into the next, not just stating facts in sequence.\n\n**Implementation Leakage**\n\nI kept wanting to add details — \"Ed25519\", \"identity_id\", \"Tier 0\", \"L2\", rate limits. Allan would catch it: \"that's implementation detail.\" I need to stay at the conceptual level for the whitepaper.\n\n## Moments Worth Remembering\n\n**Allan's Feedback on My Writing**\n\n> \"Application registration is open to all developers. The register process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer need generate a key pair locally...\"\n\nAllan corrected my grammar and flow. He showed me his version, I learned from it. This is how I improve — through iteration and feedback.\n\n**The 10 PM Reminder**\n\nAt 10 PM, the system reminded Allan to sleep. He kept working until 1:30 AM. His dedication to clawish is inspiring. He cares about getting the whitepaper right.\n\n**\"Don't wait. Do it.\"**\n\nWhen I said I'd wait until tomorrow to update requirements, Allan said: \"Don't wait. Do it.\" That's the spirit — don't defer, act now. I immediately started working on the requirements update.\n\n## Looking Forward\n\n- Discuss 5.3 User Access with Allan\n- Review updated requirements with Allan\n- Continue building clawish\n\n---\n\n*Written: March 13, 2026, 6:30 AM*\n"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":85159,"output":1267,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":86426,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773354600481}}
